  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1892400144" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1892400144" />
    <a title="Jackie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/64281380-jackie"><img alt="Jackie" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1892400144?book_show_action=true">Jan 25, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jackie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jackie" href="/user/show/64281380-jackie">Jackie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1892400144" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15846344034905066795">If you are looking for a story about anger, attraction, action, Savage Thunder will do the trick. Although the story takes similar shape to the mold of a typical captivity romance novel, it begins to lose form as the story progresses. Lindsey constantly shifts this mold by playing with race and gender roles, prompting the readers to think about much more than a happy ending. In fact, completely opposite to other romance novels, the hero seems to be the one to relinquish his control to the heroin</span>
  <span id="freeText15846344034905066795" style="display:none">If you are looking for a story about anger, attraction, action, Savage Thunder will do the trick. Although the story takes similar shape to the mold of a typical captivity romance novel, it begins to lose form as the story progresses. Lindsey constantly shifts this mold by playing with race and gender roles, prompting the readers to think about much more than a happy ending. In fact, completely opposite to other romance novels, the hero seems to be the one to relinquish his control to the heroine.<br /><br />Jocelyn Fleming, a newly widowed and sinfully pure duchess from England possesses a strange, yet undeniable beauty. Colt Thunder, a ‘half-breed’ Indian, is strong, angry, uncivilized, and Jocelyn’s complete opposite; he hates white culture, and even despises the whiteness of his own blood.<br /><br />They meet in a classic captivity narrative setting: in the middle of nowhere in the untamed American West, where the heroine is in desperate need of rescue and protection from an evil villain. Pleasantly surprised by and deeply attracted to her rescuer’s savage beauty, Jocelyn insists that Colt must accompany her to safety. Colt, despite feeling this instant attraction too, is unnerved by his interest in her beauty and voluble charm.<br /><br />Colt is constantly reminded of the last time he was attracted to a white woman, haunted by the deep and painful scarring slashed across his back. Jenny Callan did not realize Colt’s Native American blood, and once she did, there was no forgiving a ‘half-breed’ for taking her purity. The first few pages of the book recall Colt’s punishment and near death experience that still holds emotional, as well as physical scarring.<br /><br />So, in an effort to resist Jocelyn, Colt treats her harshly and cruelly. But for Colt, there is no escape. Jocelyn manages to convince him to be her guide to Wyoming, concealing her true desires to take him on as her first lover. This desire is not only physically, but also socially necessary. She feels an urgent need to rid herself from the embarrassment of being a widowed virgin, and maintain the positive reputation of her late husband, Edward. She thinks that Colt, someone so far removed from British society, and someone who can fulfill her sudden sexual fantasies, would be perfect for the job.<br /><br />I personally thought that this book was hard to read and immensely over the top at times, as evidenced by Colt and Jocelyn having sex on a horse. However, I walk away from reading this feeling, as a woman, somewhat empowered rather than defeated. All of the other few romances I’ve read usually end up with the woman conforming to the man; whatever traits she had that first attracted him to her slip away. All that was left was a woman infatuated and hopelessly in love. Romance writers got away with it; it was okay because the heroine finally found a man to care for and therefore, her needs would be satisfied.<br /><br />But by the end of Savage Thunder, Colt was the one infatuated. He was the one to give up his distinctive characteristics presented in the beginning of the novel, characteristics that Jocelyn never had to sacrifice for love. It was really refreshing to read the heroine take on a different role. Although the novel can still be problematic at times, especially pertaining to the issue of race, Lindsey does a good job of shifting gender and racial dynamics, encouraging her readers to question each role and ask the difficult questions. This novel revived my faith in romances to not only tell a story, but also to send a message.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="15846344034905066795" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


